main event: A possible unidentified flying object (UFO) was sighted near St. Petersburg, Florida on September 20, 1963 around 2330 hours.
interesting points: The object was described as slightly elongated, 30 to 50 times larger than a star, and having a definite configuration unlike a star.
The object maneuvered, traveling at speeds estimated between 300-800 mph, and made a left turn before fading out as it climbed at a 45 degree angle.
The observers included an ex-Navy navigator and navigation instructor, as well as an individual with experience in celestial navigation and private flying.
Weather conditions at the time were clear with high thin clouds and surface haze, with visibility between 2-10 miles.
A second sighting was reported by a university lecturer, who described the object as circular and white, traveling in a generally straight path that appeared to slow down and wobble.
sighted object: An elongated, star-like object and a circular, white object
witnesses: Civilian observers, including an ex-Navy navigator and a university lecturer
